, and upon original ob- __\nservations by the writer; Illustrated\nA FIELD BOOK OF THE STARS, bv William\nTyler Olcott. with over 50 diagrams and a?.\ncharts; ldmo\nSIN AND SOCIETY, by Edward A. Ross.\nBrilliant Essays by Prof. Ross, who believes that\nthe unmistakable moral decay of late brought to\nlight in business, finance and politics is trace\nable not to public Indifference, but to the inef\nfectiveness of public opinlqp in coping r __\nwith the dominant types of wrongdoing. $1.00\nTHE CONGO AND COASTS OF AFRICA, by\nRichard Harding Davis. K'o writer of today can\ndescribe people and events that he has seen\nwith greater vividness and picturesque e\npower than Mr. Davis; illustrated JM.50\nMEXICO AND HER PEOPLE OF TODAY, by\nKevin O. Winter. The customs, characteristics,\namusements, history and advancement of the\nMexicans, and the development and resources of\ntheir country. Illustrated from numerous 5;\nphotographs taken by the author. Boxed ?p2.40\nCASTLES AND KEEPS OF SCOTLAND, by\nFrank Roy Fraprle, author of \"Among Bavarian\nInns.\" etc. Much of the thrilling history and\nromance of the middle ages is necessarily con\nnected with the castles and keeps which are the\nsubject of this volume, which are haunted by\nmyriads of memories of bygone romantic days.\nWith many illustrations In color and\nduogravuie from photographs. Boxed... ?{s2.40\nCASTLES AND CHATF.AIX OF OLD NA\nVARRE AND THE BASQI'E PROVINCES, by\nFrances Mlltoun, author of \"Castles and Cha\nteaux of Old Touraine and the Loire Country.\"\nWith eight colored plates and upnard of fifty\nother illustrations by Blanche McManus.\n8vo; boxed\nJOHN HARVARD AND HIS' TIMES, bv Henry\nr Shelley. The one liook to tell the life-story\nof the founder of Harvard College, with a fresh\nnd vigorous picture of the people of his\ntimes. With 24 full-page plates .p-.UU\nTHE SEVEN AGES OF WASHINGTON, a Bi\nography. by Owen Wlster. A remarkable Inter\npretation of Its subjects. There Is not a hint of\nspread-eagleism or sentimeutnllty In the book,\nbut from beginning to end it is plain that the\nauthor has been moved to the depths of him bv\nhis hero's worth, finding in the traditionally colij\nfigure of Washington a type to touch the emo\ntions as vividly as Napoleon touches them in his\nmoat dramatic moments. Attractively bound\nadequately illustrated in photogravure, e--,\nCloth V-.OO\nMain floor. Tenth st.\nChoice Christmas Candies, pure and dainty, in splendid assortment, 15c to 80c the lb.\nWOODWARD LOTHROP.\nc(Sc.v5ffti\nWilliam F. Brown, the new president of\nColumbia Lodge of Machinists, with its\nmore than 1.500 members, was referred\nto yesterday by a brother-craftsman as\n\"the I?ittle Napoleon of the square and\ncompass.\" He was born February 15,\n186'J, and started to learn his trade in the\nordnance department of the Washington\nnavy yard in 1S78. He has been identified\nwith the labor movement for many years,\nhaving jolne 1 the Knights of Labor about\ntwenty-five years ago. Mr. Brown was\na trustee of Columbia Lodg\\ No. 374. In\nWilliam F. Brown,\nPresident-elect Columbia Ixxlfrc of Machinists.\nternational Order of Machinists, for five\nyears; was elected vice president in\nand at the recent election yvas promoted\nto the presidency.\nPresident Brown has always taken a\nlively interest in all matters affecting the\nwelfare of the thousands of workers in\nthe naval gun shops here and the navy\nyards in other sections. His friends pre\ndict that he will make a good record as\nhead of the prosperous association of\nmachinists.\nPresident Samuel Goinpers of the\nAmerican Federation of Labor went over\nto New York Monday, and on that evening\nbefore the 800 members and guests of\nthe Civic Federation he is repotted to\nhave \"said some things.\"\nHe served notice that any attempt to\nreduce the wages of workingmen at this\ntime will be \"fought to the bitter end.\"\nHe delivered the ultimatum at the din\nner given by the Civic Federation.\nJohn Mitchell also included in his speech\na similar warning to employers, although\nclothed in more temperate language.\n\"Since X have been in New York today.\"\nsaid Mr. Gompers. \"X have been ap\nproached a dozen times by bankers, linan\nclers. capitalists, in open conversation, in\nwritten communications and in whispers\nto the effect that wages must come down,\nthat the laboring man must make up liis\nmind to bear his share of the hard times\n\"And I turned to these men and 1 asked\nthem whether the soil of our country is\nless fertile, the treasures beneath the soil\nless valuable, men's minds less active, the\nlaboring men less industrious. \\V herefore.\nI .asked them, is there reason or neces\nsity to thus attack the American standard\nof our workingmen?\n\"The history of industry demonstrates\nthat every such reduction of wages, in\ntended to meet such conditions as now\nexist, has only accentuated the situation,\nmade matters worse. When you reduce\nthe laboring man's earning capacity you\nreduce his consuming power, and thereby\nintensify what was already bad enough.\nContinuing President Gompers said:\n\"So I say to the employers?to the\nbankers, the lawyers, the manufacturers,\nthe mine operators, to all employers?\nthat If they now attempt to reduce wages\nthey are not going to have the easy sail\ning that they had a few years ago. for\nthe American workingman has come to\nthe conclusion that if for any!reason the\nfinancial situation is as it is?and I shall\nnot suggest any reason tonight?it was\nnot. at any rate, due to any fault on the\npart of the working people. They have\nmade up their minds that they are not\ngoing to be the chief sufferers because of\nan artificial panic, or of one caused by\nthe blunders of those in charge of the\nfinances of the country.\"\nSpeaking along the same line Mr.\nMitchell said: \"It is not going to make\nmatters any better to reduce wages. Such\nreductions have never failed to make\nmatters worse instead of better.\"\nThousands of skilled mechanics in the\nbuilding trades are out of employment.\nIn li>0:s and l'.'ot there was so much\nbuilding that the men worked over\ntime: in 1SKJ5 the building season pro\ngressed favorably, but in 190tl it began\nto slacken somewhat.\nThis year it began badlv. and at present\nless than half of the skilled workmen are\nemployed. The prospects for the be\nginning of the new year are not en\ncouraging. but it is expected that the\nbusiness will brighten about next April.\nThe contracts al\\-eady on hand will be\nbetween $4<*>.000 and $5(10,000 more next\nyear than at present in the borough of\nManhattan, but there will be a large\nfalling oft in the Bronx and in other\nsections.\nThe trade agreements of the following\nunions having the eight-hour day ex\npire at the end of the year:\nBricklayers' and Masons' International\nUnion, who receive 70 cents per hour.\nCement Masons' Union.\" 65% cents per\nhour: laborers, skilled. 35 cents per hour;\nunskilled. 25 cents.\nBrntherhood Of Carpenters. $5 per day.\nUnited National Asociation of Pluitib\n\"rs and Steamfitters and Helpers. $5 a\nday.\nElevator Constructors ar.d Millwrights'\nI'nion. $4.50 a day.\nSheet Metal Workers' TAiion, $4.50 a\nday.\nS'nn? Setters. .*5.50 a day.\nWood Carvers' Union. $5 a day.\nThe members of the Electrical Work\ners' I'nion expected an increase from $4.50\nto $5 a day.\nThe following statement was recently\nissued on behalf of the New York Build\ning Trades Employers* Association:\n\"The business outlook is worse tiian at\nthe ibeginn'ng of 11X17, and building opera\ntions generally appear to be on the de\ncline. But reducing wages would not in\ncrease the volume of.business. Of course,\nIt would be impossible to predict abso\nlutely whether the present stagnation will\ncontinue during 1908. but next year is the\nyear of a presidential election, when trade\nis bad generally. A good deal depends\nupon the time occupied in completing the\ntunnels and other public improvements\nnow in progress. If they are finished\nsooner than is now expected it will stim\nulate building operations.\"\nDavid Mackie has been appointed audi\ntor in conjunction with the audit ng eom\nmittee of the International Association of\nMachinists for the present year.\nDUMMY FIGURE EXHIBIT.\nBloody Garments Before Jury in\nCase of Murdered Agent.\nDENVER. Col.. December lit.?Blood\nstained garments worn by Secret Service\nAgent Joseph A. \\\\\"alker on November M.\nwhen lie was shot and killed at a coal\nmine near Hesperus. Col., were exhibited\non a dummy figure yesterday to a federal\ngrand jury, which is investigating the\nkilling.\nBy the bullet holes in the clothing and\nthe testimony of the doctors who held a\npost-mortem examination over the body\nof Walker, the government expects to\nPfove that Walker/was shot from behind.\nIt is understood that District Attorney\nEarl Cranston will ask for indictments\nagainst seven men. including Joseph Van\nderweide, who says he shot Walker in\nself-dMense, and William Mason, Vander\nweide's companion at the time of the\nshooting.\nJohn S. Lehman, the aged miller who\nwas 'badly injured last Saturday while\nsuperintending some repairs at his mills\nalong the Falling springs, near Hagers\ntown, died yesterday afternoon, aged sev\nenty-cight years.\n:i:8t:nnmt:?8ntitinn:nwu%\nA. KAHN.\nLEADERS IN\nXMAS GOODS.\n?Extraordinary values\n?that merit attention.\nrt*. gold. large. I'm Inch ;4\nliockftd. dimimmi. 1 Inrh >4\nSeal King*. g?.ld; ladies*. $1 gen\ntleman's $o\nSolid fHrJKflAl* $4\nCold Sti<*k Pin*. f? monograms $1\nGold Mr?K'liC!* $1\nnff H it tons $1\nGold Shirt SnuU o>ai??nt back*\nGold Chain# Mid l*?okct? $2\nGi 14 Watch 4m N\nGold Hark t'nmlHi <c?M t.?p? $4\nGold \\Vat?-:> for ladle* ?7\nGwid foliar ltuttotw $1\nGold llut Pin* Si\nGold liiee Pin*\nGold Wat?h Chain*. f??r men $7\n(fold Hwrt<\nGold Neck Bead* J-V\nGold Society Pin,* *1\nGold Crosaca $1\nA. KAHN,\nWholesaler ami Rpuflfr ?i -J R IC C4.\nof Optii'lll Hoods. L Oil\n?loln-d.r.Su.ro\nCredit Rating\nSystems\nASK FOR CATALOG\nVasvman J*?T> fteEMreO\nMakeri of Filing Systemi\n614 Twelfth Street\nWashington\n\nPhone: 2965 Main\nKNABE\nAND OTBEB\nPIANOS\nFOB BENT.\nEXCEPTIONAL BABQAJX8 IN 8UQBTLT\nCSED PIANOS.\nBAST TERMS.\nWM. KNABE CO.,\n12J8-1220 F_Street N.W.\nofl-tf.28\nP)\nDJ\n\"Before I b?>gan using Catcarett, I bad a bad\ncomplexion. plntolea on my fare, and my food\nwas not digested us it should hare been. Now I\nam entirely well, and the pimples have all dis\nappeared from my fare. I ran truthfully say that\nTuhcarets are Jn?t ar advertised; I have takm\nonly two boxes of them.\"\nClarence II. Griffin, Sheridan, Ind.\n*0RKWHlU^\nPleasant. Palatable. Potent, Tasta Good, P?\nGood, Never Sicken. Weaken or Gripe, 10c, 25c,\n50c. Never sold In bulk. The genuine tablet\n?stamped C C. Guaranteed to cure or your\nmoney bark.\nSterling Remedy Co4 Ohlnn or N. T. 600\nsmmi sale, Tim mum mm\nHUGHES WANTS RESULTS\nTALKS WITH PUBLIC SERVICE\nCOMMISSIONERS.\nSpurs Them to Solve Transit Prob\nlems?Afraid Term Will End Be\nfore Relief Is Afforded.\nALBANY, December 10.?The leading\nfeature of the visit of th<* members of\nthe New York city public service commis\nsion to Albany yesterday was the promi\nnence of William M. Ivlns, one of the\nspecial counsel of the commission. It was\nMr. Ivins who escorted the commissioners\ninto Gov. Hughes' presence at the execu\ntive chamber, and it was the same Mr.\nIvins who sat on the right of the gov\nernor during his.dinner at the executive\nmansion last night to tlie members of the\ntwo public service commissions. In fact,\nWilliam M. Ivins seems to be Gov.\nHughes' premier 0:1 public service prob\nlems.\nIvins and Hughes Friends.\nMr. Ivins and Gov. Hughes have been\nfriends for a long time. When both were\nyoung at the practice of the law they oc\ncupied adjoining and connected offices,\nthough they were r.ot partners. This ac\ncounts for the appointment of Mr. Ivins\nas special counsel for the New York city\npublic service commission. Gov. Hughes\nwas anxious because of the lack of re\nsults in solving the New York city tran\nsit problems, and Mr. Ivins wag ap\npointed as special counsel at the sugges\ntion of the governor for the purpose of\nstirring up both the commission and the\ntraction companies.\nWhile Mr. Ivins' delving Into the affairs\nof the traction companies did not bear as\nmuch fruit as Gov. Hughes expected, still\nthe commission has begun to realise that\nthe governor wants a solution of the\ntransit problem on Manhattan Island and\nbetween the boroughs of Manhattan and\nBrooklyn which was the main reason\ngiven by the governor for the enactment\nof his public service commission law. This\nis shown by the commission's announce\nment that it will at once provide for the\nconstruction of an Kast Side subway.\nGovernor Desires Action.\nThat Gov. Hughes is disappointed In the\nwork of his New York city commission\nand that he Is seeking aid to solve the\ntransit problem elsewhere was evidenced\nyesterday when he had a. long conference\nwith Theodore P. Shonts. the president\nof the Interborough Metropolitan Hallway\nCompany. The governor and Mr. Shonts\nhad a long and earnest talk together, and\nbefore Mr. Shonts left the executive\nchamber Gov. Hughes took occasion to\nwarn him about talking to the newspaper\nmen regarding the object of the confer\nence. Consequently Mr. Shonts refused\nto discuss it. But\" the fact that Gov.\nHughes had a talk with Mr. Shonts yes\nterday afternoon before he had his con\nference with the public service commis\nsioners at the executive mansion was\ntaken as significant of the fact that the\ngovernor was trying to get the traction\ncompanies to aid his New York city pub\nlic service commissioners to solve the tran\nsit question. I\nAfter hearing arguments yesterday on\nthe motion made by District Attorney Je\nrome to compel Paul D. Cravath, personal\ncounsel for Thomas F. Ryan, to answer\ncertaiji questions before the grand Jury\nin connection with the investigation into\nthe affairs of the Metropolitan Securities\nCor:pany, Justice Rosalsky rcierved de\ncision until Monday.","height":"31044","width":"21832"}}
